  "markdown_debrief": "### ⚡ SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n**📌 S – Set the Stage (The Verdict & Diagnostic Pivot)**\n- **The Verdict:** Option **A (20%)** is correct based on the provided answer key.\n- **The Pivot Point:** The question directly asks for the **percentage of patients with bladder tumor presenting with non-muscle invasive disease**.\n\n**🎯 H – Highlight Excellence (The Surgical \"Why\" & Pathology)**\n- **Surgical Mechanism:** Bladder cancer is broadly classified into **non-muscle invasive bladder cancer (NMIBC)** and **muscle-invasive bladder cancer (MIBC)**. This distinction is critical for prognosis and treatment planning.\n    - **NMIBC** includes Ta, T1, and carcinoma in situ (CIS).\n    - **MIBC** includes T2, T3, and T4.\n- **Clinical Execution:** Accurate staging at initial presentation dictates the management strategy:\n    - **NMIBC** is typically managed with transurethral resection of bladder tumor (TURBT) followed by intravesical therapy (e.g., BCG, chemotherapy).\n    - **MIBC** often requires more aggressive treatment, such as radical cystectomy with urinary diversion, or trimodal therapy (TURBT, chemotherapy, radiation).\n- **👁️ Mental Operative Theatre:** During **TURBT**, the surgeon meticulously resects all visible tumor, ensuring deep muscle biopsies are taken to accurately determine the depth of invasion.\n    - **NMIBC** would show tumor confined to the mucosa (Ta) or lamina propria (T1), without invasion into the detrusor muscle.\n    - **MIBC** would show tumor invading the detrusor muscle (T2) or beyond.\n\n**❌ A – Address the Gaps (Systematic Distractor Demolition)**\n- **Option B (40%) (Incorrect):** This percentage is too low for NMIBC and too high for MIBC. It does not accurately reflect the typical distribution of bladder cancer stages at presentation.\n- **Option C (60%) (Incorrect):** While closer to the actual prevalence of NMIBC, it is still lower than the generally accepted range.\n- **Option D (80%) (Incorrect):** This percentage is the closest to the widely accepted epidemiological data for NMIBC presentation (typically 70-75%). If the question intended to reflect current medical consensus, this option would be the most appropriate.\n\n**📊 R – Review Learning Points (Evidence-Based Framework)**\n- **Core Principle:** The initial presentation stage of bladder cancer is a fundamental determinant of prognosis and treatment.\n\n| Classification of Bladder Cancer | Typical Presentation Percentage | Key Management Principle | Core Guideline / Surgical Society Consensus |\n| :------------------------------- | :------------------------------ | :----------------------- | :------------------------------------------ |\n| **Non-Muscle Invasive (Ta, T1, CIS)** | **~70-75%** | TURBT + Intravesical Therapy | AUA/SUO, EAU Guidelines |\n| **Muscle Invasive (T2-T4)** | **~25-30%** | Radical Cystectomy or Trimodal Therapy | AUA/SUO, EAU Guidelines |\n\n> **⚠️ Critical Guideline Updates & Textbook Conflicts**\n> - **Standard Textbooks (Sabiston / Schwartz / Campbell-Walsh Urology):** Consistently state that **approximately 70-75% of patients with bladder cancer present with non-muscle invasive disease (NMIBC)**.\n> - **Society Guidelines (AUA/SUO, EAU):** Echo these statistics, emphasizing that NMIBC is the most common presentation.\n> - **The Discrepancy:** The provided correct answer of **20% (Option A)** for non-muscle invasive disease is significantly lower than current epidemiological data and medical consensus. It is more representative of the percentage of *muscle-invasive* disease at presentation, or perhaps a very specific, atypical cohort. For a board exam, this discrepancy is critical, as selecting 20% would be medically incorrect based on current knowledge.\n\n**💡 P – Plan for Improvement (The Exam Heuristic)**\n- **The Board Pearl:** When asked about the initial presentation of bladder cancer, remember that **the vast majority (70-75%) are non-muscle invasive**, requiring TURBT and intravesical therapy, while a smaller proportion (25-30%) are muscle-invasive, often necessitating radical cystectomy."
