  "question": "Orchidopexy will reduce the frequency of malignancy occurring in the right testisMen with a history of undescended testes have an increased incidence of infertility. It is associated with lower sperm counts, sperm of poorer quality, and lower fertility rates than those of men with normally descended testes [83]. Intraabdominal and intracanalicular undescended testicles are affected similarly [84], probably related to the effect of testicular temperature on spermatogenesis [85,86]. In contrast to the risk for developing testicular cancer, there is a clear advantage to performing early orchiopexy for protection of fertility.Men with a history of undescended testis have an increased incidence of developing testicular germ cell cancers of 1 in 1000 to 1 in 2500, versus 1 in 100,000 in the general population [63-65]. Approximately 10 percent of testicular tumors occur in patients with a history of undescended testicle [66]. The risk of developing testicular cancer is affected by the location of the undescended testicle. Compared with intraabdominal testes, inguinal testes are four times less likely to become cancerous [65,67]. However, testicular malposition is not the only factor in the development of testicular cancer because 10 to 25 percent of these tumors occur in the contralateral, normally descended testicle [65,68]. In addition, surgical correction of malposition (orchiopexy) does not eliminate the risk of having testicular cancer [69].Guidelines (AAP 1996 and EAU 2012) recommend that, in otherwise healthy males, orchiopexy should be performed by 12–18 months of age, as the gonad is unlikely to descend after 6–12 months of age and there is not an added benefit from waiting.In most cases, the undescended testis is located near the neck of the scrotum, just outside or a little lateral to the external inguinal ring, in the “superficial inguinal pouch,” which is the misplaced tunica vaginalis43. Which of the following investigations is the most important to perform prior to excision of a suspected thvroglossal cyst?",
